The groove between the two mounts in not big enough for zawias_nogi_correct.stl to fit in there.

title: Wall Art LEGO Style (multicolor with single extruder)

description.text:
Always wanted some Lego minifigures on your wall?
Here is a design just for you!

This design comes in different versions:

  • multicolor print for single extruder (no multicolor printer necessary)
  • single outline
  • outline with face

Multicolor Print:

For this design you need 5 files:
01_Face_V01
02_Yellow_V01
03_Red_V01
04_Blue_V01
05_Frame_V01

You need to print them in exactly this order to make this print work.
Keep the temperature for extruder and heatbed after each print (set in your slicer or preheat your printer again after printing).

Start with 01_Face in black (eyes and mouth) and change color after each print. The next files are named after the colors I used - yellow face, red shirt, blue pants. Feel free to use the colors you like best.
End with 05_Frame in black and let it cool down completely before removing.

Each file has a built-in skirt to make it more easy to line them up correctly. The next skirt should be outside the previous (see picture above) for perfect line-up.

Do not add a brim or raft!

The files are designed for 0.2 resolution, so it's important to print in 0.2 to make it work.

I printed it in PLA, but other materials should work as well.

This design prints pretty quick and the colored parts are thin. Print in transparent material and you'll get nice window art.

For it is pretty thin you can also print it as a first layer test or to try new materials.

Outline prints:

If you like to do some additional paper crafting together with your kids or if you just like simple outlines on your wall, the outline files are for you.

The files are availlable as complete with face, outline only and face only, all in two sizes (150mm or 200mm).
The complete version has built in connections for the face to keep it in place.

To create nice art together with you kids (or just for you) print the outlines on thin cardboard (inside the .docx file) and color it as you like or use it as pattern for colored cardbord. Make sure to print in 100% size.

Cut along the outlines and glue it to the print.

If you print the version complete with face, glue the paper to the top surface and cut away the built in connections after drying.

To put it on the wall I used patafix, but poster strips etc. will work as well.

Have fun with this print and please share if you made one!

Anet AM8

0.2

The outline files can be printed with a brim for better adhesion to the buildplate, if necessary.

title: Universal conductor for organizer from the filament spool

description.text:
The device helps in converting empty spool from filament to organizer. It allows drilling holes for compartment’s axes quickly and accurately. It may be simply adjusted to spool from any manufacturer of filament that varies in height and diameters of shaft and winding.
Compartments of whole and half heights are designed as a parametric project, allowing get models for specific spool by adjustment of three table parameters, describing the variable dimensions of the spool.
The project includes also two adjustment bushings, fitting on the bayonet lock the parts of the conductor in the shaft hole of the spool, which models are generated automatically along with the compartments.
The conductor consists of two parts, the base and the “hand”, fitting in the base in slots with the angle step of 90 degrees.
Drilling is performed through metal guide holes that prevent the plastic of the appliance from smashing and melting by the drill. The guides made of stainless M3 nuts, that are tenderly fixed in a hand grip and their thread is drilled out with a drill of 3 mm. The guides are glued into both parts of the conductor into their saddles.
There are need three such guides: the one for the base and the two for the mode high “hand”.
Using the conductor:

  1. Enter the base part, optionally with its fit bushing; choose its position, that no of future holes (with angle step of 90 deg. from the first one) fail onto original openings of the spool. Drill a hole of 3 mm diameter through the guide hole, and fix the base by a M3 screw on the spool through this hole.
  2. On the same side of the spool drill 3 more holes through the guide hole of the “hand”, fitting it in slots of the base in required position.
  3. Turn the spool with the base on another side. Put on the “hand” its fit bushing and drill the 4 holes that fit exactly opposite the previous ones on the first side.

description.text:
Here's my first attempt to re-create body panels for Heathkit's HERO-1 robot. I was tired of seeing these robots sell for more than a grand when all I would do is rip out the electronics anyway.
This is my first time using Fusion 360 so be kind! I have included the Gcode from Fusion 360 and the stl file.
My geometry is a little messed up so I was unable to use the shell function, so that is why it just a solid piece. Once I learn more I can add the panel details and make a shell in 6 or 9 pieces so it will be able to print on a 200x200x200 printer. The model pictured was printed at 25%.

Please, please feel free to play around with this and it is far from complete.

UPDATE 2-28-18: Added more recess to chest panel, removed inside radius to reduce printed material.

UPDATE 3-7-18: Added HERO Jr. head STL.
I did not make the HERO jr head. That was generously given to me by a friend.

print_settings.Notes:: This mount must be printed using a flexible material such as Ninjaflex.

title: SQ11 and SQ12 mount for micro quadcopters

description.text:
This is a mount for the rather craptacular SQ11 or SQ12 cameras. They are very cheap though and light (11grams*) and currently the best option to record 720p footage on a micro quadcopter.
Personally I use it on my 118mm quad with 1103 10000kv motors.
The angle is currently set to 25 degrees, but it can be changed by modifying the OpenSCAD file.

The mount is to be printed using a flexible material such as Ninjaflex ensuring a tight fit.

The SQ11 in the photos above is modified with a wide-angle lens with a built-in IR blocking filter to improve the image quality.

*: The SQ12 weighs around 15 grams, but there are two solid pieces of metal near the lens which can be removed to free up about 3 grams. Removing the IR LED (which is rather useless ) board saves another 0.5gram.
